After the course of Bitcoin reached a maximum of 30 dollars (EUR 23) in June 2011, he fell five months later to $2 before he recovered to around $10 today (the courses are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) showed interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "like the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits" that are used to move forward in a video game that can be won or purchased by games (and sometimes also exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time storers of the accounts, auditors, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose another address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
With the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the Bitcoins handled are available in the accounts of public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This takes place via a mathematical task launched on the computers, whereas the winner, who is a kind of preliminary central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clearer electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add to it a number before the whole is "hacked".
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can hardly check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money two times very fast (less than 10 minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without a link, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer who has solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to a hundred million set, which leaves a certain gambling space...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in calculating performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and stolen the Bitcoin deposits.
"The weakness used does not concern the actual protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for payment with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also reveals these deficiencies.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
