Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the account and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November a "Mega Slot Sales" was launched.
"Three thousand dollars were exchanged," Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, converted Bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented with dealers, and the latter do not have to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be "fotografed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat assures that he has thousands of users.
It is a general trend where hierarchical systems are considered in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
"It will take some time until Bitcoin continues, but 2013 could be a turning point," he forecasts.
