Poland and the space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the Member States of the European Space Organisation ESA, Poland became the twentieth member of this Space Authority. Poland is thus the second Member State from the former Eastern Block (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The road of Poland into the space was probably beginning much earlier.
Before World War II, Polish cosmos enthusiasms were engaged in space, not always on understanding.
I remember, for example, the lecture of A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 in the Warschauer Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneer work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won in 1934 the Prix REP-Hirsch founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important defense of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines, he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's globally recognised contribution to the development of space was among other things appreciated by the name of one of the craters on the earthly side of the moon after him.
Already in 1925, a railway droisine was built in Poland for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It has not even been clarified whether the missile should be used to start or to brake the draisine.
The information on this is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with missiles.
The research was conducted by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents provided show that research had been carried out until the stage of practical tests.
The research was then freely interrupted by the entry of the German Army.
In 1937, in the special press of the design of a photoelectric hunting dragon from Ing. Rohoziński appeared, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" published by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky.
Both projects focused on the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for military use of missile technology were coordinated by the transient Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Comité Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space were published after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of an space society.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was not expected that the research of the space would have the future.
In 1956, the Polish Space Society tried to join the International Federation for Space in 1951, and the PTA became an ordinary member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year became the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), Vice-President of the International Federation for Space.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA took a major part in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests started with the two-level RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighted about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the Rakete RM-34 should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe high winds.
In 1962, however, further developments were stopped.
Follower of the first rocket of type RM was the meteor-1 rocket developed in the years 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-level missile, its total length was 510 cm and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, different from the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The meteor-1A rocket has a transport room of 0.4 litres of capacity, meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the meteor 2 missiles were developed in the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a 10 kg use load to a height of approximately 60 km.
Afterwards, the versions of meteor-2H and meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
In the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Republic of Vladimír Remek.
